@node introduction "Introduction"
AStart is a packet  mostly  for  users  with small amount of RAM. It will automatically make your system load with more memory when SHIFT is pressed and will allow you to @{" customize " link "prefs"} the things your system will and will not run upon loading with SHIFT pressed.

If you pressed the SHIFT upon loading this is called @{b}alternate mode@{ub} and only in this mode you will be able to run system with more memory.

AStart consists of two parts:
Ě @{b}alternate-startup@{ub} - the part responsible for starting up the system in alternate mode
Ěá@{b}GoForIt@{ub} - the part responsible for WBStartup drawer.

All of them can be @{" configured " link "prefs"} via the prefs program.

Since version 4, AStart now also works just fine with the following programs:
Ěá@{b}Directory Opus 5@{ub} - will run OpusBench instead of Workbench (via @{i}LoadDB@{ui} command)
Ěá@{b}MBench@{ub} - will load MBench instead of Workbench,
   @{b}WARNING!@{ub}If you intend to use MBench, you have to delete the icons of WBStartup (Enabled) and (Disabled).
Ěá@{b}HappyEnv@{ub} - will use @{b}MountENV@{ub} command to make ENV: use HappyEnv-Handler.
@endnode
@node usage "Usage"
AStart was originally designed to be used by people with rather low end machines (a person with 64MB of RAM will probably not need to save about 2Megs - this is to you, @{i}rmk@{ui} :). But AStart had a lot of modifications since the beginning, so thanks to a lot of configuration, it can be used also by high-end machines.

For the low enders, here's what you can expect:
Ě save some memory, but while the WB is still with the @{" assigns " link "ideas"}
Ě possibility to assign @{b}ENV:@{ub} to @{b}ENVArc:@{ub} or use @{b}HappyENV@{ub}
Ě assigning @{b}T:@{ub} to @{b}SYS:T@{ub}, mostly doing things that require T: assign (they say @{b}SAS/C@{ub} works better with it)

For some high enders, here's how you can use it:
Ě easily switch between WBench (@{b}startup-sequence@{ub}) and DOpus/MBench (@{b}alternate-startup@{ub})
Ě HappyENV enable/disable options - everyone loves HappyENV
Ěáyou can make a "clean" Workbench, for compatibility with other programs

Of course there are a lot of possibilities, which I haven't thought of, but are possible. If you think of something, let@{" me " link "contact"} know. I'm also open for suggestions.

A trick: If you'll hold down @{b}ALT @{ub}when WBStartup is running (start holding it before loading workbench/diropus/mbench/whatever), GoForIt will act as if it was in alternate mode (even if the computer is in normal mode).
@endnode
@node prefs "Configuring AStart"
The AStart configuration program has been rewritten and has changed a lot from the previous versions.

Here is how the prefs program works. There are 3 pages:
ĚáAlternate-Startup
ĚáGoForIt
Ě Information

The first one is used to configure @{b}alternate-startup@{ub}. The options are listed in the left list and the choices for this option in the right list. By double clicking on an option (left list), you switch it to another choice. By clicking on @{b}@{u}S@{uu}ave preferences@{ub}, the @{b}alternate-startup@{ub} will be changed with the new options. The options will be saved as well in @{b}S:AStart/@{ub} (directory had been made by the installer utility).

Under the list of options there is a list of commands to execute in alternate mode (option to run @{b}user-startup.alt@{ub} must be turned on). These files will @{b}NOT@{ub} be run in Workbench mode, but like simple commands. This was made so that commands which cannot be run in Workbench mode can still be run.

The GoForIt page is used to configure which files will and which will not be run on startup. Doubleclicking on an entry will toggle it's option (enabled/disabled). The enabled files will be run on startup, the disabled will not. The enabled files are stored in @{u}SYS:WBStartup/WBStartup (Enabled)@{uu} and the disabled ones in @{u}SYS:WBStartup/WBStartup (Disabled)@{uu}.
Also there is a list for files to be run (without having to even put them in WBStartup drawer). It is very easy to use, because you can simply sort the entries by draging (dragsorting) them. Also you can setup which files should be run in which cases. For instance you can make MCP load in alternate mode and not in normal node (if you put MCP in user-startup).

The last page cannot be configured (well, it can by me :), it is just an information about the author and registering state. Most of the data here is stored in the library.

If you quit AStart configuration program, it will save all the parameters, so you don't have to worry about saving changes like it was in AStart V2 and V3.

From V4 you can also save your prefs or some of it so that you can load it later. To do so, select @{i}Save As @{ui}from the @{i}AltStart @{ui}menu and enter the name of the file. If you wish to save only parts of the configuration, you can select which options should be saved by clicking on the extreme left column of the options list. @{fg shine}+@{fg text} means that this option should be saved. By default all options are set to be saved.

Of course if you choose to load a saved prefs file, only options saved in that file will be changed. The rest of the options will be unchanged.
@endnode
@node ideas "The main ideas of AStart"
Well, when I first thought of such a packet, I had an A1200 with just a HDD (1.2 GB :). So I was thinking about every byte of my memory, but I was nervous that most system patches also install themselves in @{b}user-startup@{ub}, so executing it (to make all the assigns I needed to work on my computer) would also run MCP and every other tool I've installed. But then I realized it:
I could convert user-startup so it would still have the assigns, but not the patches anymore. And then it hit me: DOS patterns. I could easily check if the command was Assign or ie. MCP and put it or not put it in the dest file. And so came the first BETA of AStart V1.

After that I realized that my @{b}ENVArc:@{ub} was growing bigger and bigger, so I changed the @{b}alternate-startup@{ub} to assign @{b}ENV:@{ub} to @{b}ENVArc:@{ub} instead of copying it. That was V2.

Then I put some other options like not running @{b}IPrefs@{ub}, @{b}AddDataTypes@{ub} and @{b}ConClip@{ub}, mount DOSDrivers, activate monitors etc. That was V3.

But then I got a suggestion (I think it was from Moszum, thanx) to save the options in @{b}alternate-startup @{ub}, because people were annoyed by a lot of ASTART_#? files in @{b}ENVArc:@{ub}. I added some more options, because it had new type of configuration. That is AStart V4.

I guess one could also call this page "History", he he.
@endnode
@node technical "Technical information"
Well, most of the data for AStart is stored in @{i}S:AStart/ @{ui}directory.
Here's what should be in there:
Ěáalternate-startup - the "source" for alternate-startup, it is a text with special tags for options. The format is as follows:

1. @{i}/// VARIABLENAME 0 "Name of the option, up to 48 bytes" @{ui}
2. @{i}// "Choice 0" @{ui}
3. @{i}Echo "executed lines" @{ui}
4. @{i}Echo "should be put here" @{ui}
5. @{i}// "Choice 1" @{ui}
6. @{i}Echo "and here" @{ui}
7. @{i}// "Choice 2" @{ui}
8. @{i}Echo "here too" @{ui}
9. @{i}//// @{ui}

The first line consists of the following things:
Ěá@{b}BEGINNING OF AN OPTION@{ub} - MUST BE "@{i}/// @{ui}" (with space)
Ěá@{b}VARIABLENAME@{ub} - the name of the file (in S:AStart/) to store the option number
Ě @{b}DEFAULT OPTION@{ub} - a single character which is the number of default option (like @{b}0@{ub})
Ěá@{b}"NAME OF THE OPTION"@{ub} - name to be displayed in the@{" options list " link "prefs"}, must be in commas

The second, fifth and seventh line is the beginning of the first choice:
Ě @{b}BEGINNING OF A CHOICE@{ub} - MUST BE @{i}// " @{ui}(with comma)
Ěá@{b}CHOICENAME@{ub} - name to be displayed in the@{" choices list " link "prefs"}

The 3rd, 4th, 6th and 8th lines are normal script lines. In the compilation process, only the lines in the specified option will be saved.

@{b}WARNING!@{ub} Only up to 8 options are allowed and there is no protection against it so watch it!
@{jcenter}
----
@{jleft}
@{b}GoForIt@{ub} gets its mode from @{i}S:AStart/WBSTARTUP @{ui}file and is a combination of three bits:
Ěá@{b}BIT0 (VALUE: 1)@{ub} - run @{b}enabled folder@{ub} in @{b}alternate mode@{ub}
Ěá@{b}BIT1 (VALUE: 2)@{ub} - run @{b}disabled folder@{ub} in @{b}alternate mode@{ub}
Ěá@{b}BIT2 (VALUE: 4)@{ub} - run @{b}disabled folder@{ub} in @{b}normal mode@{ub}

Of course these bits can be ORed. The @{b}enabled folder@{ub} will be run every time in @{b}normal mode@{ub}.
@{jcenter}
----
@{jleft}
The qualifier and when the machine should run in alternate mode is stored in s:alternate-startup.

The mode should be stored in the @{b}first 256 bytes@{ub} as a comment and in the following format:
@{i}; $ALTSTARTUP: <option> @{ui}
Where: @{i}<option> @{ui}is the working mode for AStart. It is recognized by the first letter and there are the following possibilites:
Ěá@{b}N@{ub}EVER - never run AStart
Ěá@{b}Q@{ub}UALIFIER - when the specified qualifier is pressed
Ěá@{b}I@{ub}NVERSE QUALIFIER - when the specified qualifier is @{b}NOT@{ub} pressed (nofmal mode only when qualifier is pressed)
Ěá@{b}A@{ub}LWAYS - always run in alternate mode

The qualifier should also be stored in the @{b}first 256 bytes@{ub} as a comment and in the following format:
@{i}; $QUALIFIER: <value> @{ui}
Where @{i}<value> @{ui}is a combination of 8 bits which are:
Ěá@{b}LEFT SHIFT @{ub} (@{b}BIT:@{ub} 0 ; @{b}VALUE:@{ub} 1)
Ěá@{b}RIGHT SHIFT @{ub} (@{b}BIT:@{ub} 1 ; @{b}VALUE:@{ub} 2)
Ěá@{b}CAPS LOCK @{ub} (@{b}BIT:@{ub} 2 ; @{b}VALUE:@{ub} 4)
Ěá@{b}CONTROL  @{ub} (@{b}BIT:@{ub} 3 ; @{b}VALUE:@{ub} 8)
Ěá@{b}LEFT ALT @{ub} (@{b}BIT:@{ub} 4 ; @{b}VALUE:@{ub} 16)
Ěá@{b}RIGHT ALT @{ub} (@{b}BIT:@{ub} 5 ; @{b}VALUE:@{ub} 32)
Ěá@{b}LEFT AMIGA @{ub} (@{b}BIT:@{ub} 6 ; @{b}VALUE:@{ub} 64)
Ěá@{b}RIGHT AMIGA @{ub} (@{b}BIT:@{ub} 7 ; @{b}VALUE:@{ub} 128)

The qualifier is considered to be pressed when @{b}at least one@{ub} of the keys which bit is set is pressed. So if you set the value to 7 it is true if either of the shifts or caps lock is pressed, @{b}not@{ub} all of them.
@{jcenter}
----
@{jleft}
Additional files to be run on WBStartup are listed in the file @{i}SYS:WBStartup/.additionalfiles @{ui}

This file is a simple text file where every line is an entry to be (or not to be, that is the question :) executed.
It's format is as follows:
@{i}YY|<pathtothefile> @{ui}
|||   |
|||   + - the path to the file (can contain assigns, but should be complete)
||+------ a break character, doesn't mean anything (can be anything)
|+------- should this file be run in alternate mode ('Y' for yes, anything else means NO)
+-------- should this file be run in normal mode ('Y' for yes, anything else means NO)

@{b}WARNING! @{ub}The 'y' also means no!
@endnode
